text: This report was produced by the United Nations Oﬀice for the Coordination of Humanitarian Aﬀairs (OCHA) Centre
label: BODY

text: for Humanitarian Data in The Hague, which manages the Humanitarian Data Exchange platform. OCHA thanks all of
label: BODY

text: the organizations that have shared data through HDX, the donors who have supported this work over the years, and
label: BODY

text: the HDX users who are committed to ensuring humanitarian response is data driven. For additional information,
label: BODY

text: contact the Centre for Humanitarian Data at centrehumdata@un.org.

text: The Centre for Humanitarian Data https://centre.humdata.org   |   Join our mailing list https://bit.ly/humdatamailing   |   Twitter https://twitter.com/humdata   |   Email centrehumdata@un.org
label: BODY

text: The goal of this report is to increase awareness of the data available for humanitarian response activities and
label: BODY

text: to highlight what is missing, as measured through OCHA’s Humanitarian Data Exchange (HDX) platform. We
label: BODY

text: want to recognize the valuable and long-standing contributions of data-sharing organizations. We also want
label: BODY

text: to be more targeted in our outreach on what data is required to understand crises so that new actors might
label: BODY

text: be compelled to join the platform. Data is not an end in itself but a critical ingredient to the analysis that
label: BODY

text: informs decision making. With nearly 168 million people in need of humanitarian assistance in 2020  — the
label: BODY

text: highest figure in decades — there is no time, or data, to lose.
label: BODY

text: When HDX was launched in 2014, it held around 800 datasets. Over the past five years, that number has
label: BODY

text: skyrocketed to over 17,000 datasets. The data covers every active humanitarian crisis, from Afghanistan to
label: BODY

text: Yemen, and has been shared by dozens of organizations, from ACLED to WFP.  In 2019, HDX was accessed by over
label: BODY

text: This is a tremendous achievement for collective action in a sector that relies on cooperation. It also shows the
label: BODY

text: value of an open data platform. OCHA’s work to aggregate data from many sources in one place has undoubtedly
label: BODY

text: created eﬀiciency in the system. Humanitarians, donors, academics, and journalists no longer need to chase
label: BODY

text: contacts to locate data; they can go to HDX and search for it. If the data is not there, the HDX team will help find it.
label: BODY

text: One downside to all of this data sharing is knowing what data is most relevant to understanding a crisis context.
label: BODY

text: In May 2019, HDX added a new feature called the Data Grid to help people in their quest for good and relevant
label: BODY

text: data. Based on extensive user research, the Data Grid places the most important crisis data into six categories:
label: BODY

text: aﬀected people; coordination and context; food security and nutrition; geography and infrastructure; health and
label: BODY

text: “Accurate data is the lifeblood of good policy and decision-making. Obtaining it,
label: BODY

text: and sharing it across hundreds of organizations, in the middle of a humanitarian
label: BODY

text: emergency, is complicated and time-consuming – but it is absolutely crucial.  ”
label: BODY

text: - United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres at the opening of the
label: BODY

text: OCHA Centre for Humanitarian Data in The Hague in December 2017
label: BODY

text: Humanitarian data is defined as: 1) data about the context in which a humanitarian crisis is occurring; 2) data about the people aﬀected
label: BODY

text: by the crisis and their needs; and 3) data about the response by organizations and people seeking to help those who need assistance.
label: BODY

text: Taken from the opening remarks of the UN Secretary-General at the launch of the Centre for Humanitarian Data in The Hague in
label: BODY

text: The Centre for Humanitarian Data https://centre.humdata.org   |   Join our mailing list https://bit.ly/humdatamailing   |   Twitter https://twitter.com/humdata   |   Email centrehumdata@un.org
label: BODY

text: Within each category, there are several sub-categories. For example, within aﬀected people, there are sub-
label: BODY

text: categories for internally displaced people, refugees, returnees, humanitarian needs, and casualties. Within
label: BODY

text: coordination and context, there are sub-categories for ‘who is doing what where’, aﬀected areas, humanitarian
label: BODY

text: access, and funding, among others. (See Annex A for all sub-category definitions).
label: BODY

text: There are three main criteria for whether relevant data is included in the Data Grid: 1) disaggregated beyond the
label: BODY

text: national level; 2) commonly-used formats; and 3) timeliness. If at least one dataset meets all criteria, that sub-
label: BODY

text: category is considered ‘complete’. If at least one dataset meets some of these criteria, the sub-category is
label: BODY

text: considered ‘incomplete’. If a dataset does not meet the criteria or does not exist on HDX, the sub-category is
label: BODY

text: considered empty or as having no data. (See Annex B for details on the Data Grid criteria).
label: BODY

text: Of course, relevant data will greatly depend on who is looking and what they are looking for. A dataset might have
label: BODY

text: the right data, but not cover the part of the country needed for the analysis. Or it might cover the right geographic
label: BODY

text: area but be in a format that is diﬀicult to work with. For this reason, the HDX team reviews all relevant datasets
label: BODY

text: and assesses them against the criteria. This careful curation process is undertaken daily on all newly shared or
label: BODY

text: updated datasets. So far, some 700 datasets have been taken through this process.
label: BODY

text: By the end of December 2019, HDX included Data Grids for 14 locations.  These include: Afghanistan, Bangladesh,
label: BODY

text: Central African Republic, Chad, Colombia, Democratic Republic of the Congo, Mozambique, Myanmar, the
label: BODY

text: Philippines, State of Palestine, Somalia, Sudan, Venezuela and Yemen. We will expand the Data Grids to cover
label: BODY

text: all locations with a Humanitarian Response Plan throughout 2020.  We may also expand the categories and sub-
label: BODY

text: As we start 2020, the completeness of all Data Grids combined is 54 percent. That is, 54 percent of relevant,
label: BODY

text: comprehensive data is available across 14 locations. If we add the data that is relevant but incomplete, the total is
label: BODY

text: 78 percent. This leaves 22 percent of categories with data that does not meet the criteria or with no data. The Data
label: BODY

text: Grids include an average of 20-30 datasets per location.
label: BODY

text: It is important to note that not all humanitarian data can be shared openly. Data about the location of aﬀected
label: BODY

text: people and responders can put people at risk, especially in conflict environments. The HDX Terms of Service
label: BODY

text: prohibit the sharing of data that includes personally identifiable information. For sensitive, non-personal data

text: • Just over 50 percent of relevant crisis data is available across 14 humanitarian operations. Afghanistan and
label: BODY

text: the Central African Republic have the most complete data, while Venezuela has the least.
label: BODY

text: • The largest data gaps are in the categories for health and education, and food security and nutrition. The
label: BODY

text: categories with the best coverage of data include aﬀected people, and geography and infrastructure.
label: BODY

text: • Partners have made tremendous progress with data sharing and use over the past several years. The
label: BODY

text: Humanitarian Data Exchange platform hosts over 17,000 datasets shared by hundreds of organizations. The
label: BODY

text: data was accessed by over 600,000 users in 2019.
label: BODY

text: • Administrative boundaries and place names are among the most critical datasets for ensuring a shared
label: BODY

text: understanding of location in an operating environment but can be diﬀicult to source and maintain.
label: BODY

text: • Although some data is sensitive and cannot be shared openly, organizations can share the metadata with the
label: BODY

text: underlying data available by request through HDX Connect. This ensures the data is protected from misuse
label: BODY

text: while also increasing transparency and avoiding duplication around what data has been collected.
label: BODY

text: • Reticence risk — the decision not to share data because of uncertainty — can be  addressed through secure
label: BODY

text: data sharing techniques and disclosure control processes.
label: BODY

text: • Predictive analytics is an exciting area with the potential to transform how response happens but models can
label: BODY

text: only work based on good data. Data cleaning is the most time consuming part of the modeling process. When
label: BODY

text: feasible, data that has been cleaned for use in models, or the modeled data itself, should be shared on HDX.
label: BODY

text: The overall figure of 54 percent complete across 14 locations masks a broad range of what is available and
label: BODY

text: missing in each location, category and sub-category. While Afghanistan and the Central African Republic have the
label: BODY

text: most relevant and comprehensive data at 63 percent complete, Venezuela has the least at 33 percent complete.
label: BODY

text: Venezuela also has the highest percentage of no data at 41 percent, illustrating the challenge of data collection
label: BODY

text: Health and education is the least complete category at 21 percent, with incomplete data for the location of health
label: BODY

text: and education facilities, and missing data for aﬀected schools. While HDX does include significant data related to
label: BODY

text: health and education statistics, this data is generally at the national level, e.g. one number for the level of primary
label: BODY

text: school enrollment in a country. We do plan to expand the Data Grid in the future to include a sub-category for
label: BODY

text: out-of-school children . We welcome feedback on other relevant data and sources to include.

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: All datasets on HDX are evaluated against the following criteria for inclusion in the Data Grid:
label: BODY

text: • Is the data in a common format? We include CSV, XLS, XLSX, SHP, etc. Formats like JSON, geopackage
label: BODY

text: and others that are more diﬀicult for the typical humanitarian data specialist would be marked
label: BODY

text: • Is the data tidy? Field names and data rows should be easy to determine. There should not be subtotal
label: BODY

text: rows interspersed with data rows. The required data for the category should be in a single table on the
label: BODY

text: same tab. For tabular data with coordinates, the x and y columns (usually longitude and latitude) should
label: BODY

text: be in decimal degree format and separated into two columns.
label: BODY

text: • Are location references defined? The dataset should contain explicit geographic data (as in GIS data or
label: BODY

text: tabular data with lat/long fields)? If not, the dataset should be joinable to an available dataset that
label: BODY

text: • Is the dataset comprehensive? If the dataset is disaggregated by administrative divisions, does it cover
label: BODY

text: all of them? If it does not, is the meaning of a missing administrative division defined in the metadata? If
label: BODY

text: there is no comprehensive list to compare against (for example with spontaneous displacement
label: BODY

text: locations), does the dataset make it clear if it attempts to be comprehensive or not?  This
label: BODY
